1. Ensemble Methods in Machine Learning

In machine learning, one model is often fragile. It can overfit data or latch onto the wrong patterns.

So researchers combine many models and let them vote or average their predictions. This is called an ensemble.

Examples:
	•	Random Forests → many decision trees vote
	•	Boosting → models sequentially correct each other
	•	Voting classifiers → multiple algorithms decide together

Why it works:

Errors made by different models tend to cancel each other out.

Simplified idea:

model A = 60% accurate
model B = 60% accurate
model C = 60% accurate

But when they vote together, accuracy can jump to 80–90% because their mistakes are not perfectly correlated.

