2. Error-Correcting Codes

Communication systems use a similar trick.

Instead of sending data once, they send redundant bits.

Example:

message: 1011
encoded: 1011 + parity bits

If noise corrupts part of the message, the extra information lets the receiver detect and repair the error.

The key principle:

redundancy → error detection → error correction

Multiple perspectives create robustness against noise.

