4. The Statistical Insight (Condorcet Jury Theorem)

There’s a famous result in political math called the Condorcet Jury Theorem.

It says:

If each decision maker has a better-than-random chance of being correct, then a majority vote among many of them becomes extremely accurate.

Example:

If each person is 60% likely to be right, then:

Number of voters	Probability majority is correct
1	60%
5	~68%
21	~82%
101	~97%

As long as their errors aren’t identical, group reasoning converges toward truth.

